# 🔴 DFS 504 Data Lineage Gaps – Compliance Report Narrative

---

## 1. Absence of End-to-End Data Lineage

The current documentation set does not provide a comprehensive, end-to-end view of how data flows across the AML and OFAC control environment. While individual documents describe systems, processes, and controls—including core banking platforms, Prime/PCS, RegTechOne, FircoSoft/Firco Continuity, and payment channels—there is no unified lineage mapping that connects these components into a single, traceable flow. Specifically, the lifecycle from data origination through ingestion, transformation, transaction monitoring, sanctions filtering, alert generation, case management, and regulatory reporting is not documented in a cohesive manner.

This fragmentation requires reviewers to infer how data moves between systems rather than rely on direct, documented evidence. As a result, the institution cannot clearly demonstrate that all relevant data is consistently captured, processed, and reported. From a DFS 504 perspective, this represents a foundational gap because the regulation requires institutions to certify that transaction monitoring and filtering programs are operating on complete and accurate data. Without end-to-end lineage, there is an inherent inability to validate that all required data flows are intact and functioning as intended.

**DFS 504.3 Alignment Gap:** Fails to meet requirements under **(a) Transaction Monitoring**, **(b) Filtering Program**, and **(c) Data Integrity**
**Sources:**       

